## Monorepo (Multiple Apps Sharing Code)

```
project-root/
├── apps/
│   ├── web/               # Web app (follows Web Application structure)
│   ├── mobile/            # Mobile app (follows Mobile structure)
│   ├── api/               # Backend API (follows API structure)
│   └── admin/             # IF your project has admin features (follows Web Application structure)
│
├── packages/              # Shared libraries
│   ├── ui/                # Shared UI components
│   ├── types/             # Shared TypeScript types
│   ├── utils/             # Shared utility functions
│   ├── validators/        # Shared validation schemas
│   └── config/            # Shared configuration (ESLint, Prettier, TS)
│
├── scripts/               # Workspace-level scripts
├── docs/                  # Shared documentation
├── contracts/             # OpenAPI / shared API contract (when multiple clients)
└── rules/                 # This rulebook
```

**Naming:** `apps/web` + `packages/*` and `website/` + `admin/` + `server/` + `shared/` are both valid. Pick one layout per repo and document it in `docs/architecture.md`. Do not mix naming schemes.

### Shared packages (monorepo) `[REFERENCE]`

When multiple deployables share types and UI, split shared code by concern - not one grab-bag package:

```
shared/   (or packages/)
├── types/         # Zod schemas, DTO types - client-safe
├── constants/     # HTTP codes, roles, route paths - client-safe
├── api-client/    # Single fetch surface for all browser apps
├── ui/            # Shared components: DataTable, Modal, forms, layout primitives
└── seed/          # Bootstrap JSON/SQL for first deploy (server/dev only)
```

- **`types` + `constants`** - importable from API, workers, and SPAs.
- **`api-client`** - used by every browser app; wraps auth headers, error parsing, base URL.
- **`ui`** - only components reused by 2+ apps or 2+ unrelated routes; route-specific UI colocates with the route (see Rules below).
- **`seed`** - never imported from browser bundles.

Add `config/` (ESLint, Prettier, TS) at workspace root when tooling is shared.

### Client-Safe vs Server-Only Code (MUST)

A shared package consumed by both client and server MUST keep server-only code (DB clients, secrets, Node built-ins, ORM, payment SDKs) out of any path the client bundle can import. Leaking it bloats the bundle and risks shipping secrets to the browser.

```
packages/shared/
├── src/
│   ├── index.ts        # CLIENT-SAFE entry - types, pure utils, constants, validators
│   └── server/
│       └── index.ts    # SERVER-ONLY entry - DB queries, secret access, Node APIs
└── package.json        # exports map: "." -> client-safe, "./server" -> server-only
```

- **Two entry points** via the package `exports` map: the default/client entry exposes only browser-safe code; a separate `./server` (or `*-server`) subpath holds everything that touches the DB, secrets, or Node built-ins.
- **Client code imports the default entry; server code imports `./server`.** A client file importing the server entry is a bug - catch it with lint (e.g. `server-only` marker / import boundary rules) or a build that fails on Node built-ins in the client graph.
- **Shared types and pure functions are client-safe** and live in the default entry so both sides reuse them without dragging in server deps.
- **Never re-export server-only modules from the client entry** - not even "just the types" if it pulls the implementation into the graph; use type-only exports if needed.

